      <h2>Safety</h2>

      <div class="danger">
        <strong>Read this entire manual before assembly or use.</strong> Failure to follow safety instructions can result in serious injury or death.
      </div>

      <h3>Safety Rules</h3>
      <ol>
        <li>Keep guards in place and in working order.</li>
        <li>Remove adjusting keys and wrenches before turning the machine on.</li>
        <li>Keep the work area clean. Cluttered areas invite accidents.</li>
        <li>Do not use in damp or wet locations. Keep the work area well lighted.</li>
        <li>Keep children away. All visitors should be kept a safe distance from the work area.</li>
        <li>Make the workshop childproof with padlocks, master switches, or by removing starter keys.</li>
        <li>Do not force the tool. It will work better and more safely at its designed rate.</li>
        <li>Use the right tool. Do not force a tool or attachment to do a job it was not designed for.</li>
        <li>Use a proper extension cord in good condition, heavy enough for the current draw.</li>
        <li>Wear proper apparel. No loose clothing, gloves, neckties, rings, bracelets, or jewelry. Wear nonslip footwear and protective hair covering.</li>
        <li>Always use safety glasses. Use a face or dust mask if the operation is dusty.</li>
        <li>Secure work with clamps or a vise when practical.</li>
        <li>Do not overreach. Always keep proper footing and balance.</li>
        <li>Maintain tools with care. Keep sharp and clean.</li>
        <li>Disconnect tools before servicing or changing accessories.</li>
        <li>Reduce the risk of unintentional starting. Ensure the switch is off before plugging in.</li>
        <li>Use recommended accessories only.</li>
        <li>Never stand on the tool.</li>
        <li>Check damaged parts before further use.</li>
        <li>Feed work into a blade or cutter against the direction of rotation only.</li>
        <li>Never leave the tool running unattended. Turn power off and wait until it stops completely.</li>
      </ol>

      <h3>Bandsaw-Specific Safety</h3>
      <ol>
        <li>Wear eye protection.</li>
        <li>Do not remove jammed cut-off pieces until blade has stopped.</li>
        <li>Maintain proper adjustment of blade tension, blade guides, and thrust bearings.</li>
        <li>Adjust the upper guide to just clear the workpiece.</li>
        <li>Hold the workpiece firmly against the table.</li>
        <li><strong>Always use a push stick.</strong> Never allow your hands or fingers close to the blade.</li>
      </ol>

      <h3>Electrical Safety &amp; Grounding</h3>
      <p>The bandsaw is equipped with an electric cord having an equipment-grounding conductor and a grounding plug. The plug must be plugged into a matching outlet properly installed and grounded per local codes. Do not modify the plug.</p>
      <p>Use only 3-wire extension cords that have 3-prong grounding plugs. Repair or replace damaged or worn cords immediately.</p>

      <div class="warning">
        <strong>Extension Cord Sizing:</strong> Use a cord heavy enough for the current draw. An undersized cord causes voltage drop, power loss, and overheating. Refer to Table A in the full PDF manual for correct gauge by cord length and ampere rating.
      </div>

      <div class="figure">
        <img src="/workshop/manuals/laguna-14cx/p05_02.png" alt="Grounding plug and outlet diagrams for 110V and 220V circuits" />
        <figcaption>Grounding plug configurations</figcaption>
      </div>

      <h3>Locking Out the Bandsaw</h3>
      <p>Never leave the bandsaw unattended and unlocked. Fabricate a cover for the control panel and use padlocks on the two handles. Push down the emergency stop before locking. This safeguards against unauthorized operation and accidental starting by children.</p>

