      <h2>Unpacking</h2>
      <p>Before unpacking, inspect the packaging for visible damage. Note all damages on delivery documents and report within 24 hours.</p>

      <div class="warning">
        <strong>The machine is heavy (264 lbs net).</strong> Do not attempt any procedure you feel is unsafe. Use two or more people to lift.
      </div>

      <p><strong>Tools required:</strong> Tin snips, knife, wrench (unpacking). Hex wrenches (assembly).</p>
      <ol>
        <li>Open the cardboard box, remove loose parts and top Styrofoam.</li>
        <li>Lift the bandsaw out of the packaging with two or more people.</li>
        <li>Lift the bottom Styrofoam and remove parts packaged underneath.</li>
      </ol>

      <h3>Parts Included</h3>
      <div class="figure">
        <img src="/workshop/manuals/laguna-14cx/p09_03.jpg" alt="Parts included with the 14CX bandsaw: fence guide bar and fence parts" />
        <figcaption>Included parts: fence guide bar and fence components</figcaption>
      </div>

      <h2>Assembly</h2>
      <ol>
        <li>Inspect packaging and internal contents for damage.</li>
        <li>Remove all components from the box. Contents include: user manual, fence, fence knuckle, hardware, cast iron table (approx. 50 lbs), and main saw assembly.</li>
        <li>Remove packaging from the main saw assembly. Get all loose Styrofoam.</li>
        <li>Install rubber feet from the hardware kit using the hex T-bar.
          <div class="note">Optional mobility kit available: &ldquo;MBA14/12 Wheel System.&rdquo; Support the bandsaw on wooden blocks, fit the swivel assembly to the back, and fit front wheels to the front. Remove the two rubber feet near the front wheels.</div>
          <div class="image-row">
            <img src="/workshop/manuals/laguna-14cx/p10_04.jpg" alt="Rubber feet installation with hex T-bar" />
            <img src="/workshop/manuals/laguna-14cx/p10_05.jpg" alt="Optional mobility kit wheel installation" />
          </div>
        </li>
        <li>Carefully stand the saw upright on a flat, level surface.</li>
        <li>Unwrap the bottom side of the table and inspect the 2 bolts on the underside &mdash; make sure they pivot freely in their slots.</li>
        <li>With assistance, lift and flip over the table so the 2 bolts line up with the 2 holes on the table mount.</li>
        <li>Verify bolts are through before releasing the table. Install 2 washers and 2 adjusting handles from the hardware kit. Tighten handles by pushing the button and turning the hub. Lock table tilt with the handle.
          <div class="image-row">
            <img src="/workshop/manuals/laguna-14cx/p11_02.jpg" alt="Table bolt alignment with mount holes" />
            <img src="/workshop/manuals/laguna-14cx/p11_03.jpg" alt="Table flipped and positioned on mount" />
            <img src="/workshop/manuals/laguna-14cx/p11_04.jpg" alt="Installing washers and adjusting handles" />
          </div>
        </li>
      </ol>

      <div class="note">
        The table has a reference stop bolt for quick alignment after tilting. The stop bolt hits the tilt-blanking disc when positioned over the table tilt hole. Moving the disc away allows the stop bolt to pass through, enabling maximum tilt (&minus;7&deg;).
      </div>

      <ol start="9">
        <li>Attach the black plastic handle to the handwheel on the top right of the machine using a 14mm wrench.
          <img src="/workshop/manuals/laguna-14cx/p11_05.jpg" alt="Attaching the black handle to the handwheel" />
        </li>
        <li>Remove plastic from the table and clean protective oil with WD-40.</li>
        <li>Install the front fence scale using 2 Hex Cap Screws (M5x0.8x10) in the upper holes on the front of the table. Adjust the scale so 0 aligns with the blade path after blade installation.
          <div class="image-row">
            <img src="/workshop/manuals/laguna-14cx/p11_06.jpg" alt="Front fence scale installation" />
            <img src="/workshop/manuals/laguna-14cx/p11_07.jpg" alt="Fence scale aligned to blade path" />
          </div>
        </li>
        <li>Attach the fence rail to the table using 2 Socket Head Cap Screws (5/16"-18x2") and 2 spacers. The hole 5-1/2" from the end should be on the left side.
          <div class="image-row">
            <img src="/workshop/manuals/laguna-14cx/p11_08.png" alt="Fence rail spacer and cap screw placement" />
            <img src="/workshop/manuals/laguna-14cx/p11_09.png" alt="Fence rail mounted on table" />
          </div>
        </li>
        <li>Fit the fence knuckle onto the fence rail by backing off the lock knob.</li>
        <li>Mount the aluminum fence to the fence knuckle. Fence can be mounted high or low. Loosen the smaller lock knobs on the side, slide the T-slot over the bracket, and lock in place.
          <div class="image-row">
            <img src="/workshop/manuals/laguna-14cx/p12_02.jpg" alt="Fence knuckle positioned on rail" />
            <img src="/workshop/manuals/laguna-14cx/p12_03.jpg" alt="Aluminum fence mounting options, high and low" />
          </div>
        </li>
      </ol>

      <div class="note">
        If the fence needs adjustment, use the nylon slider nut inside the casting to adjust up or down. Two set screws on the side of the casting adjust the fence angle.
      </div>

      <div class="image-row">
        <img src="/workshop/manuals/laguna-14cx/p12_04.jpg" alt="Fence lock knobs and T-slot bracket detail" />
        <img src="/workshop/manuals/laguna-14cx/p12_05.jpg" alt="Fence adjustment set screws on casting" />
      </div>

      <h3>Before First-Time Start</h3>
      <ol>
        <li>If not thoroughly familiar with the bandsaw, get advice from a qualified person.</li>
        <li>Ensure the machine is properly grounded and wiring codes are followed.</li>
        <li>Do not operate under the influence of drugs, alcohol, or medicine, or if tired.</li>
        <li>Always wear eye protection, safety glasses or safety shield, and hearing protection.</li>
        <li>Wear a dust mask &mdash; long-term exposure to fine dust is not healthy.</li>
        <li>Remove ties, rings, watches, and jewelry. Roll up sleeves.</li>
        <li>Ensure guards are in place.</li>
        <li>Blade teeth must point downward toward the table.</li>
        <li>Adjust the upper blade guard to just clear the material.</li>
        <li>Verify blade tension and tracking are correct.</li>
        <li>Stop the machine before removing scrap from the table.</li>
        <li>Keep hands and fingers away from the blade.</li>
        <li>Use the proper size and type of blade.</li>
        <li>Hold the workpiece firmly against the table. Use a suitable support for stock without a flat bottom surface.</li>
        <li>Use a push stick at the end of a cut, when the blade is most exposed.</li>
        <li>Hold wood firmly and feed into the blade at a moderate speed.</li>
        <li>Turn off the machine if you must back material out of an incomplete or jammed cut.</li>
      </ol>

      <h3>Testing the Saw</h3>
      <ol>
        <li>Close both doors.</li>
        <li>Verify the red Emergency Stop button is fully out.</li>
        <li>Check that the machine is clear of tools and loose objects.</li>
        <li>Confirm all adjusting and locking handles are tight.</li>
        <li>Verify no blade is installed &mdash; test without a blade for safety.</li>
        <li>Connect the bandsaw to the electricity supply.</li>
        <li>Press the &ldquo;I&rdquo; start button. The lower flywheel should turn.</li>
        <li>Test the &ldquo;O&rdquo; Stop Switch &mdash; the motor should power off and slow down.</li>
        <li>Test the red Emergency Stop button &mdash; motor should power off.</li>
        <li>Test the foot brake pedal &mdash; motor should disconnect and come to a stop.</li>
      </ol>

      <div class="danger">
        If any switch fails to operate correctly, do not use the machine until the fault is corrected.
      </div>

      <h2>Blade Changes</h2>

      <h3>Blade Installation</h3>
      <div class="warning">
        Disconnect the machine from the power source before making any adjustments.
      </div>
      <ol>
        <li>Open the top door. On the back of the saw head, locate the tensioner lever.</li>
        <li>Lower the tension lever handle to minimum, allowing the upper wheel to drop.
          <div class="note">The upper wheel may stick over time. Spray WD-40 or PB-Blaster where the tensioning slot is located. If still stuck, pull downward on the wheel.</div>
        </li>
        <li>Loosen both upper and lower blade guides.</li>
        <li>Open the red magnetic blade guard on the top section door. Open the bottom cabinet door to expose the drive pulley.</li>
        <li>Remove the plastic blade guide slider between the blade and lower area.</li>
        <li>Remove the throat plate from the worktable.</li>
        <li>Carefully unravel the blade and slide it through the slot to the throat plate area, teeth facing you (pointing downward). Slide the blade into the left-hand groove on the main frame.</li>
        <li>Work the blade around the upper and lower pulley wheels, centering as evenly as possible.</li>
        <li>Raise the tension lever handle to maximum to tighten the blade.</li>
      </ol>
      <div class="figure">
        <img src="/workshop/manuals/laguna-14cx/p13_03.jpg" alt="Blade installation path showing tension lever, guide slots, and wheel positions" />
        <figcaption>Blade installation path and tension lever location</figcaption>
      </div>

      <h3>Tensioning the Blade</h3>
      <p>The tension scale inside the top door is a reference guide based on blade width.</p>
      <ol>
        <li>Set initial tension using the scale as a guide.</li>
        <li>Fine-tune with the adjusting wheel above the worktable. <strong>Reverse thread:</strong> turn left to tighten, right to loosen.</li>
        <li>When proper tension is achieved, lock the blade with the lock knob below the adjusting wheel.</li>
        <li><strong>Deflection test:</strong> Place your finger at the 9 o&rsquo;clock position on the top wheel. Move down 6" and press the flat of the blade with moderate thumb pressure. You should get 3/16" to 1/4" of deflection.</li>
        <li>Verify blade tracking before operating.</li>
      </ol>
      <div class="image-row">
        <img src="/workshop/manuals/laguna-14cx/p14_03.jpg" alt="Blade tension adjusting wheel above the worktable" />
        <img src="/workshop/manuals/laguna-14cx/p14_04.jpg" alt="Tension lock knob below the adjusting wheel" />
      </div>

      <h2>Adjustments</h2>

      <h3>Blade Tracking / Top Idler Wheel Camber</h3>
      <p>This adjustment aligns the tilt of the idler pulley with the drive pulley.</p>
      <ol>
        <li>Rotate the upper wheel by hand while looking through the window. The blade should track in the middle of the wheels.</li>
        <li>On the back of the bandsaw, loosen the locking nut above the tensioning lever.</li>
        <li>Turn the adjusting screw-wheel clockwise to move the blade back on the wheel, or counter-clockwise to move it forward.</li>
        <li>Make adjustments while turning the upper wheel by hand until proper tracking is achieved. Lock with the lower locking knob.</li>
      </ol>
      <div class="figure">
        <img src="/workshop/manuals/laguna-14cx/p14_05.jpg" alt="Blade tracking adjustment screw on back of bandsaw, with locking nut and tensioning lever" />
        <figcaption>Blade tracking adjustment (rear view)</figcaption>
      </div>

      <h3>Blade Guide Adjustment</h3>
      <ol>
        <li>Loosen the guide assembly by turning the small knob.</li>
        <li>Pull both blade guides back to expose the rear thrust bearing.</li>
        <li>Unlock the guide post lock handle and move the guide assembly forward until the back of the blade barely touches the ceramic thrust bearing surface. Lock in place.</li>
        <li>Slide both right and left blade guides forward until the ceramic guides are about 1/8" from the gullets. Lock with the small knob on the right.</li>
        <li>Move both blade guides inward until barely touching the blade. Lock using the 2 adjustment knobs in front of the guide assembly. <strong>Do not deflect or pinch the blade.</strong></li>
        <li>Hand-track the blade through the guides for at least 2 full revolutions to verify no binding. If the weld binds, adjust guides wider by about the width of a piece of paper.</li>
        <li>Repeat for the lower blade guide assembly (easier with the table tilted to 45&deg;).</li>
      </ol>

      <div class="note">
        Rotate the rear ceramic guide approximately 15&deg; after every 8 hours of use to distribute wear evenly.
      </div>

      <div class="image-row">
        <img src="/workshop/manuals/laguna-14cx/p15_02.jpg" alt="Upper blade guide assembly showing ceramic guides, thrust bearing, and adjustment knobs" />
        <img src="/workshop/manuals/laguna-14cx/p15_03.jpg" alt="Guide assembly lock handle and guide post detail" />
      </div>

      <h3>Blade Guidepost Height</h3>
      <ol>
        <li>Loosen the guidepost locking screw on the rear top of the bandsaw.</li>
        <li>Use the handwheel above the guidepost on the side of the machine to adjust vertical position.</li>
        <li>Maintain 3/16" clearance between the guidepost and the workpiece for minimum blade exposure.</li>
        <li>Always tighten the guidepost screw after adjusting.</li>
      </ol>

      <h3>Squaring Table to Blade</h3>
      <ol>
        <li>Check that the stop bolt contacts the tilt-blanking disc.</li>
        <li>Place a square on the tabletop and bring it against the blade.</li>
        <li>If not square, loosen the lock nut on the tilt-stop bolt and adjust in small increments.</li>
        <li>Tighten the lock nut and recheck. Repeat as needed.</li>
      </ol>
      <div class="image-row">
        <img src="/workshop/manuals/laguna-14cx/p18_02.jpg" alt="Square placed against blade to check table alignment" />
        <img src="/workshop/manuals/laguna-14cx/p18_03.jpg" alt="Tilt-stop bolt lock nut adjustment" />
      </div>

      <h3>Adjusting Table Tilt</h3>
      <ol>
        <li>Loosen the lock nut and stop bolt so it does not contact the underside of the table.</li>
        <li>Loosen both locking levers on the sides of the worktable.</li>
        <li>Pivot the worktable to the desired angle using the protractor reference.</li>
        <li>Tighten the lever handles, stop bolt, and locking nut. CW = 45&deg;, CCW = 7&deg;.</li>
      </ol>

      <h3>Fence Assembly Adjustment</h3>
      <p>The fence should not rub against the table surface but be slightly above it. The gap should be equal at the front and rear.</p>
      <ol>
        <li>Loosen the fence locking wheel.</li>
        <li>Move the fence to the desired position.</li>
        <li>Lock in place by tightening the locking screw.</li>
      </ol>

      <h3>Adjusting Fence for Drift</h3>
      <ol>
        <li>Draw a straight pencil line on the edge of a board.</li>
        <li>Feed the wood into the blade, cutting next to the pencil mark. Compensate for any drift by angling the wood.</li>
        <li>Stop mid-cut and mark the angle of drift on the table with a pencil.</li>
        <li>Loosen the clamp bolts on the fence, align the fence to the pencil line, and retighten.</li>
      </ol>

      <h2>Operation</h2>

      <h3>High/Low Gear Setting &amp; FPM</h3>
      <div class="warning">
        Disconnect the machine from the power source before changing gears. The motor MUST be completely off.
      </div>
      <ol>
        <li>Turn off the machine and unplug from power.</li>
        <li>Open the bottom door. Use the adjusting handle on the back of the machine to unlock the motor position. Lift the motor adjustment lever to raise the motor and create belt slack.</li>
        <li>Move the belt to the desired pulleys:
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Rear pulleys:</strong> High gear &mdash; 160&ndash;4400 FPM</li>
            <li><strong>Front pulleys:</strong> Low gear &mdash; 60&ndash;1600 FPM</li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li>Ensure the belt is fully on the pulley before loosening the adjustment handle and lowering the motor.</li>
      </ol>

      <div class="danger">
        Never start the 14|CX with any slack in the drive belt. Doing so can cause machine damage as the belt is forced to pull through the slack.
      </div>

      <p><strong>Adjusting speed (FPM):</strong> The bandsaw must be running. Use the speed adjuster knob on the left-side control panel. Turn CW to increase speed, CCW to decrease.</p>

