      <h3>General Operating Instructions</h3>
      <ol>
        <li>Adjust the blade guide assembly to just above the workpiece (about 3/16") for minimum blade exposure.</li>
        <li>If using the fence, move it into position and lock to the guide rail. For crosscuts with the miter gauge, move the fence out of the way.</li>
        <li>Turn the machine on and wait a few seconds for full speed.</li>
        <li>Place the straightest edge against the fence and push the workpiece slowly into the blade. Let the blade do the work.</li>
        <li>When cutting long stock, use roller stands, support tables, or an assistant.</li>
        <li>When cutting at an angle with a tilted table, provide a guide against which the material can rest.</li>
      </ol>

      <div class="warning">
        Do not overfeed the blade. Overfeeding reduces blade life and increases the chance of blade breakage.
      </div>

      <h3>First-Time Operation Checklist</h3>
      <ol>
        <li>Verify blade tension, tracking, and table squareness.</li>
        <li>Connect to power. Ensure the toggle switch is on at the converter on the bottom rear of the machine.</li>
        <li>Verify the E-Stop is not depressed. Press the on button to start.</li>
        <li>Adjust speed with the speed adjustment knob.</li>
        <li>Press off to stop blade movement. The E-Stop and foot brake also stop blade operation.</li>
      </ol>

      <h2>Optional Light Kit Installation</h2>
      <p>Part No: ALEDMACH (Laguna) / 303815 (Dake)</p>
      <p>The light attaches to the top of the bandsaw. It comes with a three-pin plug for 110V or 220V. Secure the cable along the top of the bandsaw using the sticky cable clamps provided. Ensure the cable is not over the vertical shaft hole, as it could be damaged when the shaft exits.</p>
      <div class="image-row">
        <img src="/workshop/manuals/laguna-14cx/p19_02.jpg" alt="Light kit attachment point on top of bandsaw" />
        <img src="/workshop/manuals/laguna-14cx/p19_03.jpg" alt="Cable routing along the top of the bandsaw" />
      </div>
      <div class="image-row">
        <img src="/workshop/manuals/laguna-14cx/p19_04.jpg" alt="Cable clamp placement along bandsaw top" />
        <img src="/workshop/manuals/laguna-14cx/p19_05.jpg" alt="Complete light kit installation with suggested cable route" />
      </div>

      <h2>Blade Selection</h2>
      <div class="figure">
        <img src="/workshop/manuals/laguna-14cx/p20_02.png" alt="Blade selection reference chart showing tooth configurations, proper pitch indicators, and material guidance" />
        <figcaption>Blade selection reference</figcaption>
      </div>

      <h3>Tell-tale Metal Chips</h3>
      <p>Chips are the best indicator of correct feed force:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Thin or powdered chips:</strong> Increase feed rate or reduce blade speed.</li>
        <li><strong>Burned heavy chips:</strong> Reduce feed rate and/or blade speed.</li>
        <li><strong>Curly silvery and warm chips:</strong> Optimum feed rate and blade speed.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Material Hardness &amp; Pitch</h3>
      <p>The harder the material, the finer the pitch required. A variety of tooth configurations in the same width gives acceptable choices for different jobs.</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Proper pitch:</strong> Blade cuts quickly with minimum heat, feed pressure, and horsepower. Quality cuts for a prolonged period.</li>
        <li><strong>Too fine:</strong> Slow cutting, excessive heat, premature breakage or dulling, high feed pressure and horsepower.</li>
        <li><strong>Too coarse:</strong> Short cutting life, excessive tooth wear, bandsaw vibration.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Causes of Blade Breakage</h3>
      <ol>
        <li>Excessive blade thickness for the flywheel diameter.</li>
        <li>Defective weld.</li>
        <li>Incorrect tension (especially over-tensioning).</li>
        <li>Leaving blade tensioned overnight. Slacken tension when not in use.</li>
        <li>Misalignment of flywheels.</li>
        <li>Irregular flywheel surface (chip accumulation).</li>
      </ol>

      <h3>Causes of Premature Blade Dulling</h3>
      <ol>
        <li>Poorly set side guides or rear thrust guide.</li>
        <li>Poor blade tracking.</li>
        <li>Wrong blade selection (too narrow, incorrect pitch or width).</li>
        <li>Tooth pitch too fine (too many TPI).</li>
        <li>Certain woods and metals dull steel blades quickly.</li>
        <li>Painted ends on exotic woods are very abrasive &mdash; cut them off before sawing.</li>
      </ol>

      <h2>Troubleshooting</h2>

      <h3>Bandsaw Will Not Start</h3>
      <ol>
        <li>Check that the red Emergency Stop is fully pulled out.</li>
        <li>Check that the power cord is plugged in.</li>
        <li>Check the electrical supply (reset the breaker).</li>
        <li>Verify correct supply power: 110V Single Phase.</li>
      </ol>

      <h3>Squeaking Noise</h3>
      <ol>
        <li>Check the bearings.</li>
        <li>Check the drive belt.</li>
        <li>Check that the guides are adjusted correctly.</li>
      </ol>

      <h3>Upper Guide Shaft Tight or Loose</h3>
      <ol>
        <li>Clean and lubricate.</li>
        <li>Adjust rack and pinion.</li>
        <li>If the rack is bent, replace it.</li>
      </ol>

      <h3>Blade Slows During a Cut</h3>
      <ol>
        <li>Loose drive belt &mdash; re-tension.</li>
        <li>Dull blade &mdash; replace or resharpen.</li>
        <li>Feeding material too fast &mdash; slow down feed rate.</li>
        <li>Insufficient set on the teeth &mdash; change blade.</li>
        <li>Oil or dirt on the drive belt &mdash; clean or replace.</li>
        <li>Fence not aligned &mdash; realign fence.</li>
      </ol>

      <h3>Blade Will Not Track on Flywheels</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Bad blade &mdash; replace.</li>
        <li>Crown on wheels worn or damaged tire &mdash; dress the tires.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Blade Kicks</h3>
      <ul><li>Bad blade &mdash; replace.</li></ul>

      <h3>Blade Makes a Clicking Noise</h3>
      <ul><li>Bad weld &mdash; dress the weld with a grinder or replace the blade.</li></ul>

      <h3>Blade Overheats</h3>
      <ol>
        <li>Dull blade &mdash; replace or resharpen.</li>
        <li>Pitch too fine for depth of cut &mdash; change blade.</li>
        <li>Guides too tight &mdash; adjust.</li>
        <li>Material too hard for the blade &mdash; change blade.</li>
        <li>Blade too thick for wheel diameter &mdash; change blade.</li>
      </ol>

      <h3>Machine Vibrates</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Machine not level &mdash; re-level on the floor.</li>
        <li>Damaged drive belt &mdash; replace.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Machine Will Not Stop</h3>
      <div class="danger">
        Disconnect from power immediately. Do not run until repaired.
      </div>
      <ul>
        <li>Stop switch faulty &mdash; replace.</li>
        <li>Internal breaker faulty &mdash; replace.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Motor Attempts to Start but Will Not Turn</h3>
      <p>With power disconnected, open the doors and try to turn the wheel by hand. Common causes: guides too tight, wood jammed in wheel, or brake engaged.</p>

      <h3>DRO Error Codes</h3>
      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr><th>Code</th><th>Description</th><th>Solution</th></tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>Err1</td><td>Over-current protection (motor exceeds 18A for 30s)</td><td>Press Stop to reset, then Start to restart.</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Err2</td><td>Motor or spindle sensor fail</td><td>Check motor hall sensor cable, magnetic ring, spindle sensor distance (1/32"&ndash;1/8"). Replace failed components as needed.</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Err3</td><td>Overvoltage (wrong voltage input, e.g., 220V)</td><td>Check input voltage. PWM control board may need replacement (PB14CX-2-87-1).</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Err4</td><td>Undervoltage (blown fuse on PWM board)</td><td>Replace fuse: 30A 250V time-delay ceramic tube, 6x30mm.</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Err5</td><td>Communication failure between PWM and DRO boards</td><td>Check control cable connectors on both boards. Replace cable (PB14CX-37) or PWM board if needed.</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Err6</td><td>Motor runs at one speed only</td><td>Replace PWM control board (PB14CX-2-87-1).</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>

      <div class="note">
        For all error codes: press Stop to reset, then Start to restart. If errors persist, contact Laguna/Dake customer service.
      </div>

      <h2>Maintenance</h2>

      <div class="warning">
        Unplug the machine from the power source before performing any maintenance.
      </div>

      <ul>
        <li>Keep bearing guides clean and free of build-up.</li>
        <li>All bearings are sealed for life &mdash; replace when faulty.</li>
        <li>Check that the cleaning brush over the band wheel works properly. Remove deposits from band wheels to avoid vibration and blade breakage.</li>
        <li>Keep the table surface clean and rust-free. Apply talcum powder with a blackboard eraser once a week to fill casting pores and form a moisture barrier.</li>
        <li>Protect non-painted surfaces with Teflon-based lubricant.</li>
        <li>Clean and grease mechanical movement components (gears, bars) if adjustment becomes difficult.</li>
        <li>Clean and oil the tensioning mechanism if adjustment becomes difficult.</li>
        <li>Check the drive V-belt for cracks over time. Replace if irregular wear is present.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Maintenance Schedule</h3>
      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr><th>Item</th><th>Check</th><th>Interval</th><th>Action</th></tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>Saw Blade</td><td>Sound of missing teeth</td><td>While running</td><td>Replace when teeth are broken</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Saw Blade</td><td>Cut cleanness and accuracy</td><td>While running</td><td>Replace when bent or worn; use wider blade for straight cuts</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Saw Blade</td><td>Poor weld &ldquo;click&rdquo;</td><td>When changing blade</td><td>Dress weld with grinder or replace</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Saw Blade</td><td>Slippage on drive wheels</td><td>While running</td><td>Check tension; check/replace rubber tires</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Lower Drive Wheel</td><td>Bearing leakage</td><td>Monthly</td><td>Replace bearing if leaking</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Upper Drive Wheel</td><td>Bearing leakage</td><td>Monthly</td><td>Replace bearing if leaking</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Rubber Tires</td><td>Cleanliness</td><td>Daily / blade change</td><td>Wipe or brush clean</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Drive Belt</td><td>Glazing, cracks, cuts</td><td>Monthly or on slippage</td><td>Clean or replace. Do not use belt dressing.</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Ceramic Guides</td><td>Cleanliness and wear</td><td>Daily / blade change</td><td>Clean; lubricate with Teflon. Replace if worn.</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>

      <h3>Tire Maintenance</h3>
      <p>As the saw cuts, material compresses on the lower wheel tire, causing vibration, short blade life, and drift. The cleaning brush helps prevent build-up, but regular inspection is needed. Tires wear in the middle over time, causing concavity that makes tracking difficult.</p>
      <p>Sand the tire surface with 100-grit sandpaper (blade removed, wheels rotated by hand) to clean and redress the tire surface.</p>
      <div class="figure">
        <img src="/workshop/manuals/laguna-14cx/p26_02.jpg" alt="Tire surface showing wear pattern and cleaning brush contact point" />
        <figcaption>Lower wheel tire and cleaning brush</figcaption>
      </div>

      <h3>Replacing Tires</h3>
      <ol>
        <li>Remove new tire(s) from packaging and allow to rest overnight.</li>
        <li>Turn off bandsaw and disconnect power.</li>
        <li>Remove the bandsaw blade.</li>
        <li>Remove the wheel(s) by removing the securing nut.</li>
        <li>Place the wheel flat on a workbench (a dowel in a vise helps).</li>
        <li>Pry off the old tire with a scrap of wood (avoid damaging the wheel). Clean and wipe the wheel.</li>
        <li>Install the new tire. Spring clamps help hold it in place.</li>
        <li>Use a dowel between the tire and wheel to seat the tire around the circumference.</li>
        <li>Reinstall the wheel(s).</li>
      </ol>

      <h3>Replacing the Drive Belt</h3>
      <ol>
        <li>Loosen motor clamp bolts, remove tension from belt, and remove the blade. Loosen the two hex nuts holding the brake and slide it away from the disc.</li>
        <li>Remove the flywheel shaft nut clamping the wheel axle.</li>
        <li>Pull the lower flywheel off (a gear puller may be needed).</li>
        <li>Replace the drive belt.</li>
        <li>Refit the lower wheel and clamp with the shaft nut.</li>
        <li>Tension the belt and tighten motor clamping bolts.</li>
      </ol>
      <div class="note">
        Replace the belt early rather than risk a breakdown during an important job. Take care not to damage bearings during flywheel removal and reassembly.
      </div>

      <h3>Adjusting the Brake</h3>
      <p>The back brake adjuster turns clockwise to remove slack in the brake pad. The front brake adjuster is rotated clockwise with an Allen key.</p>
